The Obama Administration is taking additional actions to address the prescription opioid and heroin epidemic. They are expanding access to treatment, strengthening prescription drug monitoring, enabling safe disposal of unneeded drugs, and accelerating research on pain and opioid misuse and overdose. The Administration is calling on Congress to provide $1.1 billion in new funding for treatment. The Department of Health and Human Services is increasing the number of patients that qualified physicians who prescribe buprenorphine for opioid use disorders can treat. The Indian Health Service, Department of Veterans Affairs, and Department of Defense are implementing policies to improve prescription drug monitoring. HHS is also advancing prescriber education, encouraging safe pain management approaches, and launching new scientific studies on opioid abuse and pain treatment. The Department of Agriculture is providing funding for Distance Learning and Telemedicine projects to help rural areas address the opioid epidemic. The Drug Enforcement Administration is holding a National Prescription Drug Take-Back Day to safely dispose of unneeded prescription drugs. The Department of Housing and Urban Development is working to support individuals using medication-assisted treatment and promote best practices for housing support in recovery programs.